# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autosar-classic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Electronic systems have become an increasingly large component of the cost of an automobile, from only around 1% of its value in 1950 to around 30% in 2010.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Modern electric cars rely on power electronics for the main propulsion motor control, as well as managing the battery system.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Future autonomous cars will rely on powerful computer systems, an array of sensors, networking, and satellite navigation, all of which will require electronics.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The earliest electronic systems available as factory installations were vacuum tube car radios, starting in the early 1930s.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The development of semiconductors after World War II greatly expanded the use of electronics in automobiles, with solid-state diodes making the automotive alternator the standard after about 1960, and the first transistorized ignition systems appearing in 1963.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The emergence of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology led to the development of modern automotive electronics.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Dawon Kahng summarized in a Bell Labs memo the achievement: E.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] This led to the development of the power MOSFET by Hitachi in 1969, and the single-chip microprocessor by Federico Faggin, Marcian Hoff, Masatoshi Shima and Stanley Mazor at Intel in 1971.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The development of MOS integrated circuit (MOS IC) chips and microprocessors made a range of automotive applications economically feasible in the 1970s.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] In the early 1970s, the Japanese electronics industry began producing integrated circuits and microcontrollers for the Japanese automobile industry, used for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, dashboard, and engine control.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The Ford EEC (Electronic Engine Control) system, which utilized the Toshiba TLCS-12 PMOS microprocessor, went into mass production in 1975.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] In 1978, the Cadillac Seville featured a "trip computer" based on a 6802 microprocessor.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Electronically-controlled ignition and fuel injection systems allowed automotive designers to achieve vehicles meeting requirements for fuel economy and lower emissions, while still maintaining high levels of performance and convenience for drivers.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Today's automobiles contain a dozen or more processors, in functions such as engine management, transmission control, climate control, antilock braking, passive safety systems, navigation, and other functions.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The power MOSFET and the microcontroller, a type of single-chip microcomputer, led to significant advances in electric vehicle technology.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] MOSFET power converters allowed operation at much higher switching frequencies, made it easier to drive, reduced power losses, and significantly reduced prices, while single-chip microcontrollers could manage all aspects of the drive control and had the capacity for battery management.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used in vehicles such as automobiles, cars, trucks, electric vehicles, and smart cars.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used for the electronic control unit (ECU), while the power MOSFET and IGBT are used as the load drivers for automotive loads such as motors, solenoids, ignition coils, relays, heaters and lamps.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] In 2000, the average mid-range passenger vehicle had an estimated $100–200 of power semiconductor content, increasing by a potential 3–5 times for electric and hybrid vehicles.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] As of 2017, the average vehicle has over 50 actuators, typically controlled by power MOSFETs or other power semiconductor devices.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Another important technology that enabled modern highway-capable electric cars is the lithium-ion battery.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] It was invented by John Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino in the 1980s, and commercialized by Sony and Asahi Kasei in 1991.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The lithium-ion battery was responsible for the development of electric vehicles capable of long-distance travel, by the 2000s.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] On average, a 2020s car has 50–150 chips, according to Chris Isidore of CNN Business.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] One of the most demanding electronic parts of an automobile is the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Engine controls demand one of the highest real-time deadlines, as the engine itself is a very fast and complex part of the automobile.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Of all the electronics in any car, the computing power of the engine control unit is the highest, typically a 32-bit processor.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] A modern car may have up to 100 ECU's and a commercial vehicle up to 40.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Many more engine parameters are actively monitored and controlled in real-time.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 50 that measure pressure, temperature, flow, engine speed, oxygen level and NOx level plus other parameters at different points within the engine.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] All these sensor signals are sent to the ECU, which has the logic circuits to do the actual controlling.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The ECU output is connected to different actuators for the throttle valve, EGR valve, rack (in VGTs), fuel injector (using a pulse-width modulated signal), dosing injector and more.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 30 actuators in all.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] These control the transmission system, mainly the shifting of the gears for better shift comfort and to lower torque interrupt while shifting.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Automatic transmissions use controls for their operation, and also many semi-automatic transmissions having a fully automatic clutch or a semi-auto clutch (declutching only).
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The engine control unit and the transmission control exchange messages, sensor signals and control signals for their operation.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] All of the above systems form an infotainment system.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Developmental methods for these systems vary according to each manufacturer.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Different tools are used for both hardware and software development.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] These are new generation hybrid ECUs that combine the functionalities of multiple ECUs of Infotainment Head Unit, Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS), Instrument Cluster, Rear Camera/Parking Assist, Surround View Systems etc.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] This saves on the cost of electronics as well as mechanical/physical parts like interconnects across ECUs etc.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] There is also a more centralized control so data can be seamlessly exchanged between the systems.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Given the complexity of this hybrid system, a lot more rigor is needed to validate the system for robustness, safety and security.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] For example, if the infotainment system's application which could be running an open-source Android OS is breached, there could be possibility of hackers to take control of the car remotely and potentially misuse it for anti-social activities.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Typically so, usage of a hardware+software enabled hypervisors are used to virtualize and create separate trust and safety zones that are immune to each other's failures or breaches.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Lot of work is happening in this area and potentially will have such systems soon if not already.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] In order to minimize the risk of dangerous failures, safety-related electronic systems have to be developed following the applicable product liability requirements.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Disregard for, or inadequate application of these standards can lead to not only personal injuries, but also severe legal and economic consequences such as product cancellations or recalls.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The IEC 61508 standard, generally applicable to electrical/electronic/programmable safety-related products, is only partially adequate for automotive-development requirements.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Consequently, for the automotive industry, this standard is replaced by the existing ISO 26262, currently released as a Final Draft International Standard (FDIS).
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] ISO/DIS 26262 describes the entire product life-cycle of safety-related electrical/electronic systems for road vehicles.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] It has been published as an international standard in its final version in November 2011.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The implementation of this new standard will result in modifications and various innovations in the automobile electronics development process, as it covers the complete product life-cycle from the concept phase until its decommissioning.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] As more functions of the automobile are connected to short- or long-range networks, cybersecurity of systems against unauthorized modification is required.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] With critical systems such as engine controls, transmission, airbags, and braking connected to internal diagnostic networks, remote access could result in a malicious intruder altering the function of systems or disabling them, possibly causing injuries or fatalities.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Every new interface presents a new "attack surface".
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] The same facility that allows the owner to unlock and start a car from a smartphone app also presents risks due to remote access.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Auto manufacturers may protect the memory of various control microprocessors both to secure them from unauthorized changes and also to ensure only manufacturer-authorized facilities can diagnose or repair the vehicle.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] Systems such as keyless entry rely on cryptographic techniques to ensure "replay" or "man-in-the-middle attacks" attacks cannot record sequences to allow later break-in to the automobile.
[src:autosar-classic/automotive-electronics] In 2015 the German general automobile club commissioned an investigation of the vulnerabilities of one manufacturer's electronics system, which could have led to such exploits as unauthorized remote unlocking of the vehicle.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The objectives are scalability to different vehicle and platform variants, transferability of software, consideration of availability and safety requirements, cooperation between different partners, sustainable use of natural resources and maintainability during the product lifecycle.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] AUTOSAR was formed in July 2003 by Bavarian Motor Works (BMW), Robert Bosch GmbH, Continental AG, Mercedes-Benz Group AG, Siemens VDO and Volkswagen AG to develop and establish an open industry standard for the automotive electrical-electronic (E/E) architecture.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] In November 2003, the Ford Motor Company joined as a Core Partner.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] In the following December Peugeot Citroën Automobiles S.A. and the Toyota Motor Corporation followed.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] In November of the following year, General Motors Holding LLC also joined as a Core Partner.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] After Siemens VDO was acquired by Continental in February 2008, Siemens VDO is no longer independently represented as a Core Partner of AUTOSAR.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Since 2003, AUTOSAR has provided four major versions of the standardized automotive software architecture for its Classic Platform and one release, along with the version of acceptance tests.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] In 2013, the AUTOSAR consortium introduced a continuous working mode for the Classic Platform to maintain the standard and provide selected improvements (including releases R4.2, and 1.0 of acceptance tests).
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] In 2016, work began on the Adaptive Platform.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] An initial release (17-03) was published in early 2017, followed by release 17–10 in October 2017 and release 18–03 in March 2018.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] With release 18–10 in October 2018, the major development activities were published.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] AUTOSAR aims to establish a global standard for software and methodology, enabling open E/E system architectures for future intelligent mobility.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] This vision focuses on ensuring high levels of dependability, particularly in terms of safety and security.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] AUTOSAR provides specifications for basic software modules, defines application interfaces, and builds a common development methodology based on a standardized exchange format.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The basic software modules made available by the AUTOSAR layered software architecture can be used in vehicles from different manufacturers and electronic components from different suppliers, thereby reducing expenditures for research and development.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Based on this principle, AUTOSAR aims to prepare for upcoming technologies.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The motivation behind AUTOSAR is to manage the increasing complexity of software and E/E systems as their functional scope expands.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The initiative is designed to support flexibility in product modifications, upgrades, and updates, while leveraging scalable solutions within and across product lines.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Enhancing scalability and flexibility in the integration and transfer of functions is a key objective, aiming to improve the quality and reliability of software and E/E systems.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The goals of AUTOSAR include addressing future vehicle requirements such as availability, safety, software upgrades, updates, and maintainability.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] AUTOSAR seeks to enhance scalability and flexibility for function integration and transfer.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Additionally, the initiative aims to increase the use of "Commercial off the Shelf" software and hardware components across product lines, promoting software reuse.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] By accelerating development and maintenance processes, AUTOSAR intends to improve the management of product and process complexity and risk, while optimizing the costs associated with scalable systems.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The purpose of the foundation standard is to enforce interoperability between the AUTOSAR platforms.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The foundation contains common requirements and technical specifications (for example protocols) shared between the AUTOSAR platforms, and the common methodology.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The AUTOSAR classic platform is the standard for embedded real-time ECUs based on OSEK.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The architecture distinguishes between three software layers that run on a microcontroller: application, runtime environment (RTE) and basic software (BSW).
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The application software layer is mostly hardware independent.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Communication between software components and access to BSW happens via RTE, which represents the full interface for applications.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Services are divided further, into functional groups representing the infrastructure for system, memory and communication services.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] One essential concept of the Classic Platform is the Virtual Functional Bus (VFB).
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] This virtual bus is an abstract set of RTEs that are not yet deployed to specific ECUs and decouples the applications from the infrastructure.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] It communicates via dedicated ports, which means that the communication interfaces of the application software must be mapped to these ports.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The VFB handles communication within the individual ECU and between ECUs.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] From an application point of view, no detailed knowledge of lower-level technologies or dependencies is required.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] This supports hardware-independent development and usage of application software.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The Classic Platform also enables the integration of non-AUTOSAR systems such as GENIVI, now renamed COVESA, by using the Franca Interface Definition Language (Franca IDL).
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Standardization of functional interfaces across manufacturers and suppliers and standardization of the interfaces between the different software layers is seen as a basis for achieving the technical goals of AUTOSAR.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Only by standardizing concrete interface contents in their physical and temporal representation allows achieving the needed integration compatibility.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] New use-cases required the development of the adaptive platform.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] One example is automated driving, in the context of which the driver temporarily and/or partially transfers responsibility for driving to the vehicle.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Further, Car-2-X applications require interaction to vehicles and off-board systems.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] That means that the system has to provide secure on-board communication, support of cross-domain computing platforms, smartphone integration, integration of non-AUTOSAR systems, and so on.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Also, cloud-based services will require dedicated means for security, such as secure cloud interaction and emergency vehicle preemption.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] They will enable remote and distributed services, such as remote diagnostics, over the air (OTA) update, repair, and exchange handling.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] To support dynamic deployment of customer applications and to provide an environment for applications that require high-end computing power AUTOSAR is currently standardizing the AUTOSAR Adaptive Platform.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Its core is an operating system based on the POSIX standard.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The operating system can be used by the application via a subset of the POSIX according to IEEE1003.13 (namely PSE51).
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] One of the key features of the Adaptive Platform is service-oriented communication since the Platform is based on the Service - Oriented Architecture.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Adaptive AUTOSAR is developed and written using C++ which is an object-oriented programming language.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The communication protocol used for the in-vehicle networking is SOME/IP, based on Ethernet.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Two types of interfaces are available: services and application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The platform consists of functional clusters which are grouped in services and the AUTOSAR adaptive platform foundation.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Functional clusters in AUTOSAR Adaptive Platform have to have at least one instance per (virtual) machine while services may be distributed in the in-car network.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The adaptive platform contains both specification and code.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] In comparison to the Classic Platform, AUTOSAR develops an implementation to shorten the validation cycle and illustrate the underlying concepts.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] This implementation is available to all AUTOSAR partners.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] AUTOSAR defined six different levels of membership.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Core Partners are since 2026 AUMOVIO (AUMOVIO Germany GmbH), BMW (BMW AG), Bosch (Robert Bosch GmbH), Denso, GM (General Motors Holding LLC), Huawei (Huawei Technologies Co.Ltd.), Mercedes-Benz (Mercedes-Benz Group AG), Toyota (TMC), Vector (Vector Informatik GmbH) and VW (Volkswagen AG).
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] These companies are responsible for organization, administration and control of the AUTOSAR development partnership.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Within this core, the executive board defines the overall strategy and roadmap.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The Steering Committee manages day-to-day non-technical operations and admission of partners, public relations and contractual issues.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The chairman and Deputy of chairman, appointed for one year, represent the Steering Committee for that purpose.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] The AUTOSAR Spokesperson takes over the communication with the outside world.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Premium Partner Plus companies support the project leader team in the various technical, organizational and everyday processes.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] They also give new strategic inputs to the project leader round.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Premium and Development members contribute to work packages coordinated and monitored by the Project Leader Team established by the Core Partners.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Associate partners are making use of the standard documents AUTOSAR has already released.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Attendees are currently participating with Academic collaboration and non-commercial projects.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Selection of vendors, including RTOS, BSW, design tools, compiler, etc.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Vendors which provide related tools and software, e.g. for testing, diagnostics, development, etc.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] AUTOSAR takes part in various events every year.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] Furthermore the AUTOSAR Open Conference (AOC) is planned every year to network and give an overview over the newest achievements.
[src:autosar-classic/autosar] A list of the events which are planned can be found on the AUTOSAR website.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:autosar-classic/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] A precise and stable characteristic feature is that no or not all functions of embedded software are initiated/controlled via a human interface, but through machine-interfaces instead.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Manufacturers build embedded software into the electronics of cars, telephones, modems, robots, appliances, toys, security systems, pacemakers, televisions and set-top boxes, and digital watches, for example.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] This software can be very simple, such as lighting controls running on an 8-bit microcontroller with a few kilobytes of memory with the suitable level of processing complexity determined with a Probably Approximately Correct Computation framework (a methodology based on randomized algorithms).
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] However, embedded software can become very sophisticated in applications such as routers, optical network elements, airplanes, missiles, and process control systems.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Unlike standard computers that generally use operating systems such as macOS, Windows or Linux, embedded software may use no operating system.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] When they do use one, a wide variety of operating systems can be chosen from, typically a real-time operating system.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Code for embedded software is typically written in C or C++, but various high-level programming languages, such as C#, Java, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Assembly languages are often used too, especially in booting and interrupt handling.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Ada is used in some military and aviation projects.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Most consumers are familiar with application software that provide functionality on a computer.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] However embedded software is often less visible, but no less complicated.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Unlike application software, embedded software has fixed hardware requirements and capabilities, and addition of third-party hardware or software is strictly controlled.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Embedded software needs to include all needed device drivers at manufacturing time, and the device drivers are written for the various hardware devices.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] The software is highly dependent on the CPU and specific chips chosen.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Most embedded software engineers have at least a passing knowledge of reading schematics, and reading data sheets for components to determine usage of registers and communication system.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Conversion between decimal, hexadecimal and binary is useful as well as using bit manipulation.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Web applications are often used for managing hardware, although XML files and other output may be passed to a computer for display.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] File systems with folders are typically used, however SQL databases are often absent.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Software development requires use of a cross compiler, which runs on a computer but produces executable code for the target device.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Debugging requires use of an in-circuit emulator, and debugging hardware such as JTAG or SWD debuggers.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Software developers often have access to the complete kernel (OS) source code.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Size of the storage memory and RAM can vary significantly.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Some systems run in 16 KB of Flash and 4 KB of RAM with a CPU operating at 8 MHz, other systems can rival contemporary computers.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] These space requirements lead to more work being done in C or embedded C++, instead of C++.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Interpreted languages like BASIC (while e.g.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Parallax Propeller can use compiled BASIC) and Java (Java ME Embedded 8.3 is available for e.g.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] ARM Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7 microcontrollers and older ARM11 used in Raspberry Pi and Intel Galileo Gen.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] 2) are not commonly used; while an implementation of the interpreted Python 3 language – MicroPython – is however available expressly for microcontroller use, e.g.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] 32-bit ARM-based (such as BBC micro:bit) and 16-bit PIC microcontrollers.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Communications between processors and between one processor and other components are essential.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Besides direct memory addressing, hardware level common protocols include I²C, SPI, serial ports, 1-Wires, Ethernets, and USB.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Communications protocols designed for use in embedded systems are available as closed source from companies including InterNiche Technologies and CMX Systems.
[src:autosar-classic/embedded-software] Open-source protocols stem from uIP, lwip, and others.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:autosar-classic/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The *architecture* of a software system is a metaphor, analogous to the architecture of a building.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] It functions as the blueprints for the system and the development project, which project management can later use to extrapolate the tasks necessary to be executed by the teams and people involved.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture is about making fundamental structural choices that are costly to change once implemented.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture choices include specific structural options from possibilities in the design of the software.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] "Architectural Kata" is a teamwork which can be used to produce an architectural solution that fits the needs.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Each team extracts and prioritizes architectural characteristics (aka non functional requirements) then models the components accordingly.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The team can use C4 Model which is a flexible method to model the architecture just enough.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Note that synchronous communication between architectural components, entangles them and they must share the same architectural characteristics.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Documenting software architecture facilitates communication between stakeholders, captures early decisions about the high-level design, and allows the reuse of design components between projects.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture design is commonly juxtaposed with software application design.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architectures can be categorized into two main types: monolith and distributed architecture, each having its own subcategories.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture tends to become more complex over time.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architects should use "fitness functions" to continuously keep the architecture in check.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] There is no sharp distinction between software architecture versus design and requirements engineering (see Related fields below).
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] They are all part of a "chain of intentionality" from high-level intentions to low-level details.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The following architectural anti-patterns can arise when architects make decisions.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] These anti-patterns often follow a progressive sequence, where resolving one may lead to the emergence of another.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture is an "intellectually graspable" abstraction of a complex system.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The comparison between software design and (civil) architecture was first drawn in the late 1960s, but the term "software architecture" did not see widespread usage until the 1990s.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The field of computer science had encountered problems associated with complexity since its formation.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Earlier problems of complexity were solved by developers by choosing the right data structures, developing algorithms, and by applying the concept of separation of concerns.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Although the term "software architecture" is relatively new to the industry, the fundamental principles of the field have been applied sporadically by software engineering pioneers since the mid-1980s.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Early attempts to capture and explain software architecture of a system were imprecise and disorganized, often characterized by a set of box-and-line diagrams.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture as a concept has its origins in the research of Edsger Dijkstra in 1968 and David Parnas in the early 1970s.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] These scientists emphasized that the structure of a software system matters and getting the structure right is critical.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] During the 1990s there was a concerted effort to define and codify fundamental aspects of the discipline, with research work concentrating on architectural styles (patterns), architecture description languages, architecture documentation, and formal methods.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Research institutions have played a prominent role in furthering software architecture as a discipline.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Mary Shaw and David Garlan of Carnegie Mellon wrote a book titled *Software Architecture: Perspectives on an Emerging Discipline* in 1996, which promoted software architecture concepts such as components, connectors, and styles.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The University of California, Irvine's Institute for Software Research's efforts in software architecture research is directed primarily in architectural styles, architecture description languages, and dynamic architectures.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] IEEE 1471-2000, "Recommended Practice for Architecture Description of Software-Intensive Systems", was the first formal standard in the area of software architecture.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] In November 2011, IEEE 1471–2000 was superseded by ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011, "Systems and software engineering – Architecture description" (jointly published by IEEE and ISO).
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] This reflects the relationship between software architecture, enterprise architecture and solution architecture.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Making architectural decisions involves collecting sufficient relevant information, providing justification for the decision, documenting the decision and its rationale, and communicating it effectively to the appropriate stakeholders.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] It's software architect's responsibility to match architectural characteristics (aka non-functional requirements) with business requirements.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] There are four core activities in software architecture design.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] These core architecture activities are performed iteratively and at different stages of the initial software development life-cycle, as well as over the evolution of a system.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The outputs of the analysis activity are those requirements that have a measurable impact on a software system's architecture, called architecturally significant requirements.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Architecture requires critical supporting activities.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] These supporting activities take place throughout the core software architecture process.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] They include knowledge management and communication, design reasoning and decision-making, and documentation.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture supporting activities are carried out during core software architecture activities.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] These supporting activities assist a software architect to carry out analysis, synthesis, evaluation, and evolution.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] For instance, an architect has to gather knowledge, make decisions, and document during the analysis phase.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture inherently deals with uncertainties, and the size of architectural components can significantly influence a system's outcomes, both positively and negatively.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Neal Ford and Mark Richards propose an iterative approach to address the challenge of identifying and right-sizing components.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] This method emphasizes continuous refinement as teams develop a more nuanced understanding of system behavior and requirements.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] This cycle serves as a general framework and can be adapted to different domains.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] There are also concerns that software architecture leads to too much big design up front, especially among proponents of agile software development.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] A number of methods have been developed to balance the trade-offs of up-front design and agility, including the agile method DSDM which mandates a "Foundations" phase during which "just enough" architectural foundations are laid.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] *IEEE Software* devoted a special issue to the interaction between agility and architecture.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture erosion refers to a gradual gap between the intended and implemented architecture of a software system over time.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The phenomenon of software architecture erosion was initially brought to light in 1992 by Perry and Wolf alongside their definition of software architecture.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture erosion may occur in each stage of the software development life cycle and has varying impacts on the development speed and the cost of maintenance.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture erosion occurs due to various reasons, such as *architectural violations*, *the accumulation of technical debt*, and *knowledge vaporization*.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] A famous case of architecture erosion is the failure of Mozilla Web browser.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Mozilla is an application created by Netscape with a complex codebase that became harder to maintain due to continuous changes.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Due to initial poor design and growing architecture erosion, Netscape spent two years redeveloping the Mozilla Web browser, demonstrating the importance of proactive architecture management to prevent costly repairs and project delays.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Architecture erosion can decrease software performance, substantially increase evolutionary costs, and degrade software quality.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Various approaches and tools have been proposed to detect architecture erosion.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] These approaches are primarily classified into four categories: consistency-based, evolution-based, defect-based, and decision-based approaches.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] For instance, automated architecture conformance checks, static code analysis tools, and refactoring techniques help identify and mitigate erosion early.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Besides, the measures used to address architecture erosion contain two main types: preventative and remedial measures.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Preventative measures include enforcing architectural rules, regular code reviews, and automated testing, while remedial measures involve refactoring, redesign, and documentation updates.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Software architecture recovery (or reconstruction, or reverse engineering) includes the methods, techniques, and processes to uncover a software system's architecture from available information, including its implementation and documentation.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Architecture recovery is often necessary to make informed decisions in the face of obsolete or out-of-date documentation and architecture erosion: implementation and maintenance decisions diverging from the envisioned architecture.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Practices exist to recover software architecture as static program analysis.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] This is a part of the subjects covered by the software intelligence practice.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Architecture is design but not all design is architectural.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] In practice, the architect is the one who draws the line between software architecture (architectural design) and detailed design (non-architectural design).
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] There are no rules or guidelines that fit all cases, although there have been attempts to formalize the distinction.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] For example, the client–server style is architectural (strategic) because a program that is built on this principle can be expanded into a program that is not client–server—for example, by adding peer-to-peer nodes.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Requirements engineering and software architecture can be seen as complementary approaches: while software architecture targets the 'solution space' or the 'how', requirements engineering addresses the 'problem space' or the 'what'.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Requirements engineering entails the elicitation, negotiation, specification, validation, documentation, and management of requirements.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Both requirements engineering and software architecture revolve around stakeholder concerns, needs, and wishes.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] In short, required behavior impacts solution architecture, which in turn may introduce new requirements.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Approaches such as the Twin Peaks model aim to exploit the synergistic relation between requirements and architecture.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Serverless architecture is a cloud computing paradigm that is often misunderstood as being server-free.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] It essentially shifts server management responsibilities from developers to cloud service providers.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] This allows businesses to run their backend code on cloud infrastructure, eliminating the need for physical server management.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The event-driven approach of serverless architecture relies on small, task-specific functions that are executed on-demand.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] These functions are known as Function as a Service (FaaS), and they offer cost-efficiency through a pay-as-you-go billing model and dynamic resource scaling based on application demand.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] The main concern addressed by the systems architecture is then the integration of software and hardware in a complete, correctly working device.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] is to "translate business vision and strategy into effective enterprise".
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] , usually distinguish between different enterprise architecture layers.
[src:autosar-classic/software-architecture] Enterprise architecture addresses among others the alignment between these layers, usually in a top-down approach.
